<div class="entry entry-content" style="margin:0px; padding:0px">
<p style="margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:20px; padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
This post covers to use Apache flume to gather customer product search clicks and store the information using hadoop and elasticsearch sinks. The data may consist of different product search events like filtering based on different facets, sorting information,
 pagination information and further the products viewed and some of the products marked as favorite by the customers. In later posts we will analyze data further to use the same information for display and analytic.</p>
<h2 style="margin:10px 0px 20px; padding:0px; font-size:18px; color:rgb(10,10,10)">
Product Search Functionality</h2>
<p style="margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:20px; padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
Any eCommerce platform offers different products to customers and search functionality is one of the basics of that. Allowing user for guided navigation using different facets/filters or free text search for the content is trivial of the any of existing search
 functionality.</p>

<h2 style="margin:10px 0px 20px; padding:0px; font-size:18px; color:rgb(10,10,10)">
Apache Flume</h2>
<p style="margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:20px; padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
<a target="_blank" href="https://flume.apache.org/" rel="nofollow" title="" class="ext-link" style="text-decoration:none; color:rgb(50,102,147)">Apache Flume</a> is used to gather and aggregate data. Here Embedded Flume agent is used to capture Search
 Query instruction Events. In real scenario based on the usage,</p>
<ul style="margin:20px 0px 20px 30px; padding:0px; list-style:square; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
<li style="margin:0px; padding:0px">Either you can use embedded agent to collect data</li><li style="margin:0px; padding:0px">Or through rest api to push data from page to backend api service dedicated for events collections</li><li style="margin:0px; padding:0px">Or you can use application logging functionality to log all search events and tail the log file to collect data</li></ul>
<p style="margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:20px; padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
Consider a scenario depending on application, multiple web/app servers sending events data to collector flume agent. As depicted in the diagram below the search clicks events are collected from multiple web/app servers and a collector/consolidator agent to
 collect data from all agents. The data is further divided based on selector using multiplexing strategy to store in Hadoop HDFS and also directing relevant data to ElasticSearch, eg. recently viewed items.</p>
<p style="margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:20px; padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
<a target="_blank" href="http://a3ab771892fd198a96736e50.javacodegeeks.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flume-dataflow-agent-sinks.png" rel="nofollow" style="text-decoration:none; color:rgb(50,102,147)"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-25688" src="http://a3ab771892fd198a96736e50.javacodegeeks.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flume-dataflow-agent-sinks-300x188.png" alt="flume-dataflow-agent-sinks" width="300" height="188" style="border:1px solid rgb(224,224,224); display:block; margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto; margin-bottom:10px; padding:5px; vertical-align:bottom"></a></p>

<h2 style="margin:10px 0px 20px; padding:0px; font-size:18px; color:rgb(10,10,10)">
Store Search Events Data</h2>
<p style="margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:20px; padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
Flume provides multiple sink option to store the data for future analysis. As shown in the diagram, we will take the scenario to store the data in Apache Hadoop and also on ElasticSearch for recently viewed items functionality.</p>
<h3 style="margin:10px 0px 20px; padding:0px; font-size:16px; color:rgb(10,10,10)">

To test the application how the search query instructions behave on your existing hadoop instance, setup the hadoop and elasticsearch instances separately. The application uses Cloudera hadoop distribution 5.0 for testing purpose.</p>
<p style="margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:20px; padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
In later post we will cover to analyze the generated data further,</p>
<ul style="margin:20px 0px 20px 30px; padding:0px; list-style:square; color:rgb(51,51,51); font-family:Arial,serif; font-size:14px; line-height:22.81999969482422px">
<li style="margin:0px; padding:0px">Using Hive query the data for top customer queries and number of times a product viewed.</li><li style="margin:0px; padding:0px">Using ElasticSearch Hadoop to index customer top queries and product views data</li><li style="margin:0px; padding:0px">Using Pig to count total number of unique customers</li><li style="margin:0px; padding:0px">Using Oozie to  schedule coordinated jobs for hive partition and bundle job to index data to ElasticSearch.</li></ul>
